{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492527"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:34:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:34:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1091"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1091"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.21,0.41,0.1,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52865"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1091"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38245"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"632"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15470"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52865"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of cramping lower abdominal pain.. Her bowel habit is normally regular, but she has been constipated for the last two days. She does not have any urinary symptoms. Her last menstrual period was two years ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft, with some tenderness in the left iliac fossa. A plain abdominal X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the radiological findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uterine fibroid","Phleboliths","Ovarian teratoma","Gallstone ileus","Bladder calculi"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows several calcified areas in the pelvis, some of which resemble teeth. This radiological finding is most consistent with a mature cystic teratoma, also known as a dermoid tumour. \u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian teratomas\u003C/strong\u003E often contain complex and well-developed structures such as hair, teeth, or bone, which can be visible on X-ray as calcifications. These benign lesions are typically incidental findings and may not be related to the patient\u0027s presenting symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine fibroids\u003C/strong\u003E can occasionally calcify, but the pattern tends to be more uniform and would not typically resemble teeth. Moreover, fibroids are usually not visible on plain X-ray unless heavily calcified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhleboliths\u003C/strong\u003E are small, round calcifications in veins, usually seen in the pelvis. However, the calcifications in this image are much too large and irregularly shaped to be phleboliths.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallstone ileus\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with symptoms of small bowel obstruction, which are not prominent in this case. Additionally, a gallstone would usually appear as a single, more uniformly calcified, ovoid structure, often in the right upper quadrant or small bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder calculi\u003C/strong\u003E would likely cause urinary symptoms, which this patient does not have. Bladder stones also tend to have a more uniform appearance and would be located in the midline lower pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the radiological findings suggest an ovarian teratoma, it\u0027s important to note that this is likely an incidental finding. The patient\u0027s presenting symptoms of left iliac fossa pain and constipation are more suggestive of other conditions, such as diverticulitis. Further investigations, such as a CT scan or ultrasound, would be warranted to confirm the diagnosis of the teratoma and to evaluate the cause of the patient\u0027s current symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ovarian teratomas are usually incidental findings on imaging.","Mature cystic teratomas (dermoid tumours) often contain complex structures such as teeth or bone.","Abdominal X-rays can sometimes reveal characteristic calcifications of ovarian teratomas."],"references":["Sahin H, Abdullazade S, Sanci M. Mature cystic teratoma of the ovary: a cutting edge overview on imaging features. Insights Imaging 2017; 8:227-41. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28105559/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38245"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1091"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17784"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17784"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/633bdc3c-60b3-414e-a177-236025b783e0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/633bdc3c-60b3-414e-a177-236025b783e0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":696,"height":543}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38245"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-11T09:54:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T09:56:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data